s null, return \"Queue empty.\" If not, process the request and return a message that it was processed.\n\nLet me check the SOUL.md steps again. The workflow says:\n\n1. Claim a request\n2. If null: print \"Queue empty.\" and stop.\n3. If request: refine prompt, generate image, mark complete.\n\nSo the agent should run the claim command first. Let's simulate that.\n\nAssuming the claim command returns a request, the agent would then proceed. But the user's task is to process any pending requests. So the summary would be the processing results.\n\nBut since the user is expecting a summary as plain text, the agent needs to output the result of the queue check.\n\nSo the steps are:\n\n- Run the claim command.\n- If result is not null:\n  - Process the request (generate image, mark complete)\n  - Check queue again\n  - Repeat until queue is empty\n- If no requests: say queue empty.\n\nBut the cron job is a single check. However, the SOUL.md says to keep checking until queue is empty. So the agent should loop until there are no more requests.\n\nWait, the cron job is scheduled to run periodically, so the agent should process all available requests in one run. So the agent should check the queue, process each request, and then stop.\n\nSo the summary would be: \"Processed X requests.\" or \"Queue empty.\"\n\nAssuming the agent runs the claim command and gets a request, processes it, then checks again. If another request is found, process it, etc., until queue is empty.\n\nBut the user's instruction says: \"Return your summary as plain text; it will be delivered automatically.\"\n\nSo the agent needs to output a summary after processing all pending requests. For example, \"Processed 2 image generation requests.\"\n\nBut how does the agent know if it's done? It should loop until no more requests are available.\n\nHowever, the user's cron job might be designed to run and process as many as possible.\n\nGiven that the agent is silent and follows the SOUL.md, it should process